Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
attachIOBuffer(25.10)                                    attachIOBuffer(25.10)

Name
       attachIOBuffer  - Adds buffers/inverters to the I/O pins of a block and
       places the buffers/inverters near the I/O pins

Syntax
        attachIOBuffer

       [-help]

       [-baseName <baseName>]

       [-dishonorUpfDomainBoundaryCheckForIsoLsStrategy]

       [-excNetFile <excNetFileName>]

       [-excludeClockNet]

       [-port]

       [-prePlace]

       [-selNetFile <selNetFileName>]

       [-skipRefinePlace]

       [-suffix <suffixName>]

       {[-in <cellNameList>] [-out <cellNameList>]}

       [-status {placed fixed softfixed}]

       Adds buffers/inverters to the I/O  pins  of  a  block  and  places  the
       buffers/inverters near the I/O pins. When a top-level input (output) is
       connected to a power domain other than the default, the added buffer is
       matched  to  the  hierarchy of the destination (source) cell and placed
       inside the power domain.

       This command is power-domain aware. To take advantage of  this  feature
       when the netlist contains level shifters, load the shifter table before
       running this command.

       Through  the -port and -suffix parameters, you can control the instance
       and net names created when you use attachIOBuffer.

       You can use this command after loading a design. Use the -status  fixed
       parameter before you run place_design.

Parameters
       -help  Outputs  a  brief description that includes the type and default
              information for each attachIOBuffer parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the  man  command:

              man attachIOBuffer

       -baseName <baseName>
              Specifies the base name of the new nets. For nets with the  same
              base name, you should consider the hierarchical index and add 1.
              For  example,  if  there are several nets with an abc base name,
              ending on abc98, then the first new net with the same base  name
              is abc99.

              Example: attachIOBuffer -baseName buf -in BUFX4

              Before

              After

       -dishonorUpfDomainBoundaryCheckForIsoLsStrategy
              Dishonors   power-domain  boundary  check  for  isolation/level-
              shifter instances.

       -excludeClockNet
              Does not connect the buffer on clock nets. You must trigger  the
              clock  net  markings  prior  to running attachIOBuffer, with the
              timeDesign command. To  query  whether  a  given  clock  net  is
              marked, use dbIsNetClock <netName>.

       -excNetFile <excNetFileName>
              Specifies  the  file  that contains the names of nets to exclude
              from the buffer attachment operation.

       -in <cellNameList>
              Specifies the cell name or a list of cell  names  of  the  input
              (-in) buffer. If the specified cell is an inverter, then the at-
              tachIOBuffer command inserts an inverter pair.

              Note:  If  the  -in  and -out parameters are specified together,
              both input and output pins will be  attached  buffers/inverters.
              If  only  -in (or -out) option is specified, then only input (or
              output) pins will be attached buffer. If  a  list  of  cells  is
              specified,  it  will  insert the first CPF compliant cell. It is
              recommended  to  give   non-AO   buffers/inverters   before   AO
              buffers/inverters in the list.

       -out <cellNameList>
              Specifies  the  cell  name or a list of cell names of the output
              (-out) buffer. If the specified cell is an  inverter,  then  the
              attachIOBuffer command inserts an inverter pair.

              Note:  If  the  -in  and -out parameters are specified together,
              both input and output pins will be  attached  buffers/inverters.
              If  only  -in (or -out) option is specified, then only input (or
              output) pins will be attached buffer. If  a  list  of  cells  is
              specified,  it  will  insert the first CPF compliant cell. It is
              recommended  to  give   non-AO   buffers/inverters   before   AO
              buffers/inverters in the list.

       -port  Prepends  the  port name to the name of the net or instance cre-
              ated.

              Example: attachIOBuffer -in BUFX4 -port

              Before

              After

       -prePlace
              Specifies to legally place the inverter connected  to  the  port
              and to leave the other inverter unplaced.

              Example: attachIOBuffer -in INVX2 -prePlace

       -selNetFile <selNetFileName>
              Specifies the file that contains the names of nets to include in
              the buffer attachment operation.

       -skipRefinePlace
              Skips  legalization  of  the  new  buffer/inverter  (incremental
              placement needs to be run later to legalize it).

       -status {placed fixed softfixed}
              Specifies  the  placement  status  of  the   added   buffer   as
              placed/fixed/softfixed.

       -suffix <suffixName>
              Appends a string to name of the net or instance created.

Examples
              * The  following command attaches buffers bufx4 to the I/O pins.
                The new nets have a basename of abc:

                attachIOBuffer -baseName abc -in bufx4

              * The following command prepends the port name and  appends  the
                _buf string to the name of the instance and net created by at-
                tachIOBuffer:

                attachIOBuffer -port -suffix "buf"

                Resulting instance name:

                port1_I_buf

                Resulting net name:

                port1_N_buf

